Our official documentation for the Confluence like feature instructs users that they may disable the feature if they don't want to use it. This can be done by disabling the Like plugin from the UPM. (see [http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Likes+and+Popular+Content#LikesandPopularContent-Disablingthelikefeature])

However, for OnDemand users, because the plugin is bundled as a system plugin, users are not able to disable the plugin (in OnDemand, only users with System Administrator permissions are permitted to enable or disable 'system' plugins, and the System Administrator perm is only granted to atlassian support) (see [http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/AOD/Restricted+Functions+in+Atlassian+OnDemand#RestrictedFunctionsinAtlassianOnDemand-Confluence]).

There is already an existing feature in the UPM that allows the host product to 'override' a plugins listing from 'System' to 'User-Installed', so that users are able to enable and disable it. We should perform this override for the Like plugin, also.

Since I raised a similar issue in this project, I'm cross-posting this bug report.  See [TOC-139|https://studio.plugins.atlassian.com/browse/TOC-139?focusedCommentId=60117#comment-60117] for the original.

When adding the example HTML from [the macro documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Table+of+Contents+Macro#TableofContentsMacro-Notes] to a page in an HTML macro, the expected behavior is that the TOC macro will render the heading and create a link the the anchor with a href.  Instead, the {{<a>}} is created without a href, similar to [this Confluence request|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONF-24665?focusedCommentId=311172#comment-311172].  I'm not sure if it's an issue with TOC or with the Confluence renderer mentioned in the other JAC issue.

Example HTML:
{code}
<h2><a name="pagename-headingname"></a>Heading Name</h2>
{code}

Confluence 3.5 renderer would create this HTML for the page:
{code}
<a href=​"#pagename-headingname">​Heading Name​</a>​
{code}

Confluence 4.2 renderer creates this HTML instead:
{code}
<a name=​"pagename-headingname">​Heading Name​</a>​
{code}

